  "text": "Autoantibodies to a 49-kDa protein were detected in 6 of Table 4 ). Only 3 of these 62 patients had a titer of more than 1:1000: 1 each with Addison's disease, rheumatoid arthritis, and a postoperative pituitary tumor. Other polypeptides were detected by individual sera (e.g. an 88-kDa band was seen in two patients, one illustrated in Fig. 1, lane 4) , but because these were not consistently present in hypophysitis cases, they will not be further considered here. Immunoblotting is known to detect multiple autoantigens [CITATION_1] . Nonspecific binding was seen in all experiments at approximately 25, 50, and 64 kDa with second antibody alone and was reduced by depleting the pituitary cytosolic fraction of IgG. It was not seen when animal tissues were used. Human Igs from blood present in the pituitary glands at homogenization are the most likely explanation.",
